The north campus social chairman and soutll campus
:ocean chairman asked house council and baffleboard members
or a pledge to efforts open room policy last Sunday. Their
reasons were treat they could not take responsibility for an
unenforced open room program this semester and that the
college was in serious danger of losing the program if such
a pledge were not made.
Yesterday, the two chairman met with the social planning
board to decide the fate of open rooms this semester. The
rogram of open rooms was extended to all but the four
cialis—barnes, South counter, liable, and Langan—which
failed to guarantee enforcement.
The action has had some opportunity aspects. First,
there was no claim from the administration that college officials were any more seriously concerned with enforcement
procedures recently than in past computers.
Second, there was no pressure from the administration
for a statement of this nature if open rooms were to be
presented; the possibility that a new dean of men might review
the program next fall and the fact that no opens were scheduled during the interim session (nor have there been any
during past interior) were the only “threats.”
Third, the action was hourly times. House councils were
even only a few days to decide whether to sign the pledge.
ad a similar proposal been raised later in the semester,
after open roolns for this semester had been scheduled and
assured, there would have been time to discuss and which
the alternatives.
Fourth, the purpose of the proposal was not explained
accurately. The result was widespread uncertainty in many
balls. Many house council members simply didn’t want to
lodge themselves to be ubiquitous petroleum. Others felt
hat the pledge implied previous laxity ill enforcement Others
didn‘t feel a pledge by this year’s house councils would
guarantee a confirmation of enforcement next year.
The Board of Trustees, however, has never skilled out
what steps would be requiring to making the present expert»
mental program permanent. Perhaps the reason for the under'
senate present situation is that no one knows the exact mature
qualities we are supposed to be displaying. ls student responsibility to be measured by student ability to strictly efforts present rules? Should we efforts less strictly and see
that rumors of the “irresponsible minority” area’t spread? Or
are there other qualities the administration and the Board
of Trustees would like us to manifest?
Most students want open rooms to continue; at present
no one is sure of what we are supposed to do to ensure their
confirmation. J
W
Students tend to be very short-fighter when they look
[or the answer to Grinnell’s open form policy. Although they
can say a great deal concerning the situation, the attitude
previous that the less done about it the better.
The head social chairman of North and South campus
must be explained for what appears to be outstanding courage
along with an impressive amount of insight. They were not
afraid to admit that their program would most likely fail
to function properly under existing conditions. Neither did
they hide the fact. that responsible action involved positive
student enforcement. chairs was a lonely action of selfrespollsihility. ‘
Students were checked, at first, that they were being
called upon to act. Many had failed to acquaint themselves
with the concept that positions of leadership detailed more
than the acceptance of pUSlt10n#f01‘ in the past year there
have been many accepting positions, and few giving leadership.
The idea of students affecting that they would take that
responsibility of enhancing open forms caused a lot of static
across campus. But, by the end of the week the majority
of students had indicated that they were willing to take the
responsibility for their positions in a new effort to efforts the
open form policy. If such action can be carried out, it will
add to the value of the policy itself and will undoubtedly
solve some of its problems. Perhaps in time it will lead to
an expanded and improved program.
Those who refused to afford a position of enforcement
and gave no reason for this refused were able to lose themselves in booty phrases about the demands of the proposition,
or about self made theories on rules in general. (This does
not include those calls which didn’t sign the o iginal statement out drew up corporations of their own indicating their
desire to continue enforcement.) But those reducing to sign
any document could not hide the simple facts. Their refused
